		<header>
			
			<h1>Executive Brief Update 2011: WTO Agreement on Agriculture</h1>

						<div class="pdf-file">
				<a href="/en/layout/set/print/content/download/12079/495644/file/fe3a193c430b6f4123a793fc795734a7.pdf">Download <img src="/extension/agritrade/design/agritrade/images/pdf.gif" alt=""/></a>
			</div>
			
			<h4>
									</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p><b>About this update</b></p><p>This brief was updated in July 2011. The original executive brief was published in August 2008 and is available on request from agritrade-mail@cta.int</p><p>Other publications in this series and additional resources on ACP—EU agriculture and fisheries trade issues can be found online at http://agritrade.cta.int/</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<a name="eztoc495634_1" id="eztoc495634_1"></a><h2><b>1. Background and key issues</b></h2><p>While World Trade Organisation (WTO) negotiations have little direct impact on the terms of access for ACP exports to EU markets, these being largely covered by the duty-free quota-access provisions of the Everything But Arms (EBA) initiative and (I)EPAs, the WTO does provide the international framework for both the EU’s and the ACP’s wider trade relations. This includes rules related to tariffs, the use of export promotion measures and the deployment of domestic support to the agriculture sector. There is therefore a range of issues in the WTO affecting both ACP–EU agricultural trade relations and the value of the preferential market access that ACP countries enjoy.</p><p>Developments in the WTO can also have a bearing on ACP members’ efforts to promote regional integration and diversify their trading partners. Developments in and around the WTO Agreement on Agriculture have both a direct and an indirect bearing on ACP–EU agricultural trade relations.</p><p>Traditionally ACP agricultural concerns in the WTO context have been divided into five areas:</p>
<ul>

<li>preserving the right to use certain traditional trade policy tools;</li>

<li>the trade consequences of domestic support measures in OECD countries; </li>

<li>export competition, via export subsidies and other forms of direct export support;</li>

<li>market access (including preference erosion); </li>

<li>cotton sector issues. </li>

</ul>
<p>In 2008 the issue of high food prices was added to this list of ACP concerns, evolving into calls for targeted initiatives on commodity issues.</p><p>On the use of traditional trade policy tools, some individual ACP governments wish to retain the space in policy making to use tools, such as import licensing and export taxes, as an integral part of targeted, sector-specific agricultural development strategies.</p><p>On domestic support the ACP group has called for:</p>
<ul>

<li>a real and substantial reduction in the use of domestic support</li>

<li>the end of <i>de minimis</i> support for developed economies; </li>

<li>the introduction of disciplines on blue-box support at a product-specific level. </li>

</ul>
<p>On export competition the ACP group has called for:</p>
<ul>

<li>a credible end date for the complete elimination of export subsidies and other equivalent forms of export support; </li>

<li>arrangements for food aid that accommodate the needs of net food-importing developing countries and food aid recipients; </li>

<li>provisions on state trading enterprises that allow ACP governments to continue to use such institutions. </li>

</ul>
<p>On market access the ACP group has called for:</p>
<ul>

<li>the issue of preference erosion to be addressed concretely and comprehensively;</li>

<li>the granting of full duty-free, quota-free (DFQF) access for LDCs to all OECD and advanced developing country markets, and for LDCs ‘to get the Round for free’; </li>

<li>full access to the special safeguard mechanism (SSM) through procedures which allow effective protection against import surges. </li>

</ul>
<p>On cotton issues the ACP has called for:</p>
<ul>

<li>the immediate elimination of export subsidies; </li>

<li>the immediate reduction of production support in the cotton sector and its rapid phasing out; </li>

<li>complete duty-free access for LDC cotton and cotton products to all OECD markets; </li>

<li>the establishment of compensatory development assistance programmes for ACP cotton producers. </li>

</ul>
<p>The ACP group has called for specific measures to address instability in commodity prices and for the needs of small and vulnerable economies (SVEs) to be fully addressed within all relevant provisions.</p><p>The EU’s approach to the WTO agricultural negotiations is rooted in the EU common agricultural policy (CAP) reform process, notably in securing international acceptance of new forms of direct aid payment. The shifting balance between trade policy tools and financial support instruments within the CAP sets the parameters for the EU position in the Doha Development Round.</p><p>The EU is looking increasingly to shift WTO negotiations towards the removal of non-tariff barriers to trade and towards addressing a range of ‘behind border’ issues.</p><a name="eztoc495634_2" id="eztoc495634_2"></a><h2><b>2. Latest developments</b></h2><p><b>2.1 Progress in the negotiations</b></p><p><b>&nbsp;</b>During 2010 a two-pronged approach to the negotiation process was consolidated. This consists of continuing technical consultations and negotiations at the multilateral level, and smaller bilateral and plurilateral consultations designed to test and explore potential outcomes. While some small group discussions have yielded results, notably resolving the banana dispute, concerns have been expressed that the outcomes they generate can vary significantly from multilaterally agreed texts (see section 2.5). The plurilateral agreement on the treatment of preference erosion products alongside the banana deal was questioned by a number of WTO members who maintained that the products selected for inclusion as ‘preference erosion’ products varied significantly from the agreed December 2008 WTO agriculture modalities text (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Topics/WTO/Progress-on-preference-erosion-products-but-pessimism-overall" target="_self">Progress on “preference erosion” products but pessimism overall</a>’, March 2010).</p><p>ACP governments for their part have ‘deplored’ the deal concluded bilaterally between the USA and Brazil to resolve their WTO cotton dispute. These views highlight the difficulties of trying to move multilateral negotiations forward through parallel processes of plurilateral negotiations (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Topics/WTO/Cotton-and-the-reassertion-of-ACP-concerns-in-the-Doha-process" target="_self">Cotton and the reassertion of ACP concerns in the Doha process</a>’, March 2011).</p><p>Overall, meetings during 2010 to take stock revealed a lack of substantive progress on agricultural issues, including those of greatest interest to the ACP, namely issues around:</p>
<ul>

<li>cotton;</li>

<li>sugar;</li>

<li>bananas;</li>

<li>preference erosion;</li>

<li>the elimination of export refunds;</li>

<li>the flexibilities granted to developed economies; </li>

<li>the special safeguard mechanisms. </li>

</ul>
<p>Even on preference erosion, where agreement on the approach appeared to be emerging, the critical issue of which products are to be designated preference erosion products, and hence subjected to special treatment, was left unresolved.</p><p>Calls from ACP/LDC countries for ‘early harvest’ in the form of resolution of issues that are central to the development dimension of the Doha Round have largely fallen on deaf ears. In particular these countries have called for an early resolution of the cotton issue and the full extension of DFQF access to LDCs. This has led some analysts to argue that development-related issues are falling off agenda of the Doha Development Round (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/WTO/State-of-Doha-negotiations-reviewed-by-South-Centre" target="_self">State of Doha negotiations reviewed by South Centre</a>’, June 2010).</p><p>This has led to a situation where WTO Director-General Pascal Lamy in effect relaunched the negotiations in December 2010 by calling for WTO members to conclude negotiations by the end of 2011. Agricultural negotiations restarted in mid January with the aim of having an updated negotiating text by the end of March 2011, stressing that the new draft text would have to be a bottom-up process, and would rely on the members themselves making new compromise proposals. However by the end of March 2011 little progress was evident (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Topics/WTO/Negotiations-relaunched-but-not-necessarily-re-energised" target="_self">Negotiations relaunched by not necessarily re-energised</a>’, January 2011)</p><p>In mid February 2011, Brazil proposed that market opening for key farm products such as beef, pork and poultry, dairy products, sugar and rice, ‘should go beyond levels currently proposed … in return for the greater market access for manufactures’ to developing country markets. Such concessions in the WTO could variously involve ‘capping tariffs or cutting them more deeply than previously proposed’, leading to a ‘top-up to the agriculture text’. Such a ‘top-up’ would see ‘greater market access for farm goods … “calibrated” with market opening in other areas’. This proposal received a cool reception from developed country governments, suggesting little enthusiasm from OECD countries for further agricultural market opening, beyond that already on the table (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Topics/WTO/Agricultural-market-access-remains-at-heart-of-WTO-deal" target="_self">Agricultural market remains at heart of WTO deal</a>’, April 2011).</p><p>While agricultural market access issues remain at the heart of any WTO deal, there is, despite high world market prices, little enthusiasm for new concessions. Increasingly the negotiation of agricultural tariff concessions is being taken into bilateral forums (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/EU-FTAs/EU-farmers-release-data-on-concerns-over-EU-Mercosur-negotiations" target="_self">EU farmers release data on concerns over EU–Mercosur negotiations</a>’, April 2011).</p><p><b>2.2&nbsp; Progress on cotton issues</b></p><p><b>&nbsp;</b>ACP cotton producers have been in the forefront of efforts to end OECD trade-distorting export and production subsidies in the cotton sector. West African cotton producers (the so-called C4 group of Mali, Burkina Faso, Chad and Benin) have tabled specific proposals at the WTO for a substantial, accelerated reduction of OECD cotton subsidies and their total elimination as soon as possible. Interim demands have been tabled for transitional measures for LDCs to provide compensation to offset income losses arising from OECD policies.</p><p>In WTO parlance the C4 group called for:</p>
<ul>

<li>the extension of the concept of ‘special products’ to the offensive interests of developing countries, such as the export of such products being essential for agricultural development or the survival of the rural population;</li>

<li>explicit recognition that cotton is a ‘special’ product for development and poverty reduction in LDCs and, as such, should benefit from special treatment to ensure fair access to global markets;</li>

<li>the total elimination of border measures, domestic support, and all forms of subsidies for the export of cotton.</li>

</ul>
<p>The little progress achieved led the ACP to release a statement on 27 January 2011, arguing that a solution to the cotton problem ‘cannot wait’, and calling for an ‘immediate resumption’ of negotiations on the cotton issue based on the December 2008 draft modalities (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Topics/WTO/Cotton-and-the-reassertion-of-ACP-concerns-in-the-Doha-process" target="_self">Cotton and the reassertion of ACP concerns in the Doha process</a>’, March 2011). This was followed on 15 March by the launching of the WAEMU cotton initiative, intensifying lobbying for C4 cotton concerns to be addressed in both the 2013 process of CAP reform and the revision of the US Farm Bill. This initiative aims essentially to secure ‘a substantial reduction or even elimination of domestic subsidies that distort international cotton trade’. (See <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Commodities/Cotton/WAEMU-cotton-initiative-launched" target="_self">WAEMU cotton initiative launched</a>’, April 2011.)</p><p>The January statement expressed particular concern over the bilateral accommodation reached between the US and Brazil to resolve Brazil’s challenge to US cotton subsidies which had been taken to the WTO dispute settlement process. The April 2010 US–Brazil bilateral agreement has three components:</p>
<ul>

<li>an offer to Brazil of US$147.3 million per year in a ‘technical assistance’ fund;</li>

<li>a commitment to making changes to an export credit programme supporting overseas buyers purchasing US cotton;</li>

<li>a commitment to begin opening up the US market to imports of Brazilian meat products.</li>

</ul>
<p>In exchange for these concessions Brazil agreed to ‘hold off’ from retaliatory trade measures. This agreement was consolidated in June 2010 with a framework for dealing with cotton issues in the context of a review in Congress of the US Farm Bill.</p><p>Some Brazilian observers argued that the deal ‘does not go far enough to right the wrongs of US cotton subsidies’, as it ‘lacked the symbolism of change’ in US policy that Brazil sought with its WTO suit.</p><p>This interim resolution of the US–Brazil cotton dispute would appear to reduce the pressure on the US to make concessions on cotton at the WTO, without there being a broader agreement. Current high world market prices of cotton notwithstanding, this would leave the C4 countries of West Africa fully exposed to the fluctuations of distorted global cotton markets. This would appear to be particularly the case in view of the projected 12% expansion in US cotton sowings in response to high global cotton prices (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Topics/WTO/Cotton-and-the-reassertion-of-ACP-concerns-in-the-Doha-process" target="_self">Cotton and the reassertion of ACP concerns in the Doha process</a>’, March 2011). It is unlikely that such a rapid expansion of the area under cotton would have been possible without US production being sustained at higher levels during periods of low prices by the systems of public sector assistance available to its cotton farmers.</p><p><b>Table 1: Cotton outlook ‘A’ index, middling 1-3/32 inch staple, CIF Liverpool, US cents/lb</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
