<p><b>2.3 The debate on the treatment of sugar </b></p><p><b>&nbsp;</b>While there were no significant developments in the treatment of EU sugar sector tariffs and trade measures in the WTO negotiations, the context of these negotiations has been transformed by price developments on world sugar markets. Currently EU bound tariff rates on white sugar and raw sugar for refining are €419/tonne and €339/tonne respectively. This places sugar in the category requiring the highest level of tariff cuts under a WTO agreement.</p><p>Traditionally ACP sugar sector stakeholders have argued for sugar to be treated in the WTO negotiations as a ‘long-standing preference’ product (i.e. a ‘sensitive product’), a view reiterated in May 2010. At a dedicated workshop on CAP reform and the ACP sugar sector, ACP sugar sector stakeholders also expressed support for the EU to be allowed to make use of the Special Safeguard Clause for sugar for as long as possible. This view however was articulated at a time of falling world market prices, during a quarter of the year when world market prices were on average 17.5% below EU sugar prices. A different view might transpire if world market sugar prices were consistently above EU sugar prices, as occurred in the fourth quarter of 2010.</p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<td width="443" valign="top">  <p class=" text-center"><b>Additional related ACP sugar sector stakeholder demands</b></p><p>In addition to calls for the treatment of sugar as a ‘sensitive product’ in the WTO negotiations, ACP sugar sector stakeholders have called for:</p>
<ul>

<li>the continued use of production quotas as a sugar market management tool under the CAP;</li>

<li>the maintenance of EU sugar reference prices;</li>

<li>a limitation of the expansion of tariff-rate quota (TRQ) access for sugar under bilateral FTA arrangements;</li>

<li>the accommodation of any additional TRQ access granted through a reduction in EU sugar production quotas.</li>

</ul>

  </td>
</tr>

</table>
<p>On the assumption that world market prices would remain substantially below EU sugar market prices, the initial EU policy perspective was gravitating towards treating sugar as a ‘sensitive product’. Such a designation would allow the EU to introduce lower tariff reductions than would be generally required, but in exchange for an expansion of tariff-rate quota access to the EU market. Depending on the level of deviation from the standard tariff reductions which the EU sought for sugar (two-thirds, one-half, one-third), the additional TRQ access which the EU would be required to grant would range between 500,000 and 850,000 tonnes. The tariff charged under these additional quotas must be the same as the lowest bound rate for existing TRQs, which under the EU’s current schedule is zero. This expanded access would need to be phased in over 7 years.</p><p>In contrast, a straight tariff cut without any deviation and with no expanded TRQ access would need to be phased in over an 8-year period. Even without expanded TRQ access, the EU would be allowed to maintain some level of tariff protection for sugar for 8 years. In addition, the continuation of special safeguard provisions would provide additional levels of protection for the EU sugar sector.</p><p>Treating sugar as a sensitive product is therefore appropriate if, for a sustained period of time, world market sugar prices are likely to remain below EU sugar market prices. Standard tariff protection would be too little to prevent a flood of sugar imports from low cost suppliers such as Brazil, meaning a need for special tariff treatment and expanded TRQ access. If, however, world market prices remained relatively close to EU market prices, or, as occurred from the fourth quarter of 2010 and first quarter of 2011, world market prices were above EU market prices, then standard tariff protection would probably be sufficient to prevent a flood of imports.</p><p><b>Table 2: Average sugar prices on markets open to ACP sugar exporters (US cents/lb)</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
