<p><b>&nbsp;</b>Sources:</p><p>US market prices: IMF</p><p>
<a href="http://www.indexmundi.com/commodities/?commodity=sugar-us-import-price" target="_self">http://www.indexmundi.com/commodities/?commodity=sugar-us-import-price</a></p><p>EU market prices: IMF</p><p>
<a href="http://www.indexmundi.com/commodities/?commodity=sugar-european-import-price&amp;months=60" target="_self">http://www.indexmundi.com/commodities/?commodity=sugar-european-import-p...</a></p><p>World market prices: IMF</p><p>
<a href="http://www.indexmundi.com/commodities/?commodity=sugar&amp;months=60" target="_self">http://www.indexmundi.com/commodities/?commodity=sugar&amp;months=60</a></p><p><b>&nbsp;</b>Indeed, with a situation of high world market prices, ACP exporters may continue to divert raw sugar supplies away from the EU market towards national and regional markets. In this context, in the short term EU raw sugar refiners would be likely to face continued difficulties in securing sufficient supplies. However, as exportable production in the ACP expands, these supply problems would ease regardless of relative EU and world market prices.</p><p>Viewed from an ACP perspective, with the volatility of global sugar prices and the euro–US dollar exchange rate (a crucial determinant of the relative attractiveness of EU and world markets for sugar), there is considerable uncertainty over what would be the most appropriate treatment of sugar in the WTO.</p><p><b>2.4&nbsp; Developments in banana issues</b></p><p>On 15 December 2009 an agreement was reached to end the long-running WTO banana dispute. This will see the EU cut tariffs from €176/tonne to €114/tonne by 2017. The first tariff cut of €28 will be retroactively applied to 15 December 2010, once the necessary procedures for the incorporation of the agreement into national legislation have been completed. Further tariff reductions are to take place in seven annual stages starting in January 2011.</p><p>The December 2009 agreement duly entered into force on 31 May 2010. The retroactive tariff cut reportedly only benefited EU importers who reclaimed the duty, and not Latin American banana exporters. Despite the limited distribution of short-term gains, Latin American banana exports are expected to increase significantly in response to the tariff reductions.</p><p>The impact of the WTO banana agreement also needs to be seen against the additional tariff reductions in the FTA agreements with Colombia, Peru and five Central American countries. Under these bilateral trade agreements duties on bananas will fall progressively to €75 by 2020. Ecuadorian banana exporters are therefore currently pressing their government to renew FTA negotiations with the EU, to secure the additional quota-restricted tariff concessions the latter has made available on a bilateral basis to fellow Latin American banana exporters.</p><p>A European Parliament background study for the approval process for the Geneva banana deal projected a decline in the market share of both ACP and EU banana producers. Significantly, while in January 2011 the European Parliament’s trade committee approved the December 2009 banana deal, ‘both [the European Parliamentary Left/Nordic Green Left] and [the Greens/European Free Alliance] groups voted against granting Parliament’s consent’, since ‘the deal would jeopardise the basic rights of small producers by strengthening the monopoly position of big US multinationals controlling the banana market in Latin American countries’.</p><p><b>2.5&nbsp; Dealing with preference erosion products </b></p><p><b>&nbsp;</b>In parallel with the conclusion of the December 2009 banana deal, discussion took place on the approach to dealing with preference erosion products. The EU, Latin American and ACP governments agreed to ‘jointly promote’ an approach to tropical products and preference erosion products in the ongoing Doha Development Round negotiations. This would defer tariff cuts in ‘preference erosion’ products, with the parties concerned presenting plans for these cuts to the WTO.</p><p>Agreement was reached that listed preference erosion products should be subject to ‘gentler and slower tariff cuts’ (phased in over 10 years, rather than 5). According to ICTSD reports, it was agreed that preference erosion products would need to meet two criteria, namely, they had to be ‘sensitive’ and account for ‘more than 10% of domestic consumption on a given tariff line between 2003 and 2005’. Where products were treated as ‘preference erosion products’ then ‘quotas … would be expanded in equal annual instalments over a period of seven years’. However the crucial issue of which products are to be classified as preference erosion products and thereby subject to such special treatment was left unresolved.<b>&nbsp;</b></p><p>Additionally, products such as cut flowers, sugar, fruits and their juices, arrowroot, peanut oil and tobacco appear on the agreed list of products to receive preferential treatment as preference erosion products. While there was a desire to ring-fence the preference erosion compromise ‘so that momentum could be built for a conclusion to the WTO’s Doha Round trade talks’, a number of WTO members were ‘irritated’ by the products selected for inclusion as ‘preference erosion’ products. They saw these products as ‘significantly different from those agreed as part of the December 2008 WTO agriculture modalities’. One negotiator described the ‘preference erosion’ agreement as ‘a plurilateral agreement that needed to be multilateralised’ – exemplifying the difficulties of trying to move multilateral negotiations forward through parallel processes of plurilateral negotiations.</p><a name="eztoc495634_3" id="eztoc495634_3"></a><h2><b>3.&nbsp; Implications for the ACP</b></h2><p><b>3.1 Prospects for an agreement</b></p><p><b>&nbsp;</b>It is unclear that the political will exists to address the compromises that will need to be made to reconcile conflicting positions. In the agricultural sector the absence of any reference in the EC communication on the future of the CAP to its long-standing commitment to abolish export subsidies within a WTO context would suggest that a finalisation of the Doha Round in 2011 may not be fully realistic. It is equally unclear whether ACP concerns on the actual production and trade effects of ‘non-trade-distorting forms of support’ (given the scale of such programmes) will be addressed. Indeed, if progress begins to be made in the negotiations, ACP governments will need to take care to ensure that their concerns over matters such as preference erosion and the actual trade effects of decoupled direct aid payments are not just ignored.</p><p>Overall there is growing ACP concern that their priorities will be left aside as the major developed and advanced developing countries push for the finalisation of a Doha Round Agreement. The side deal between the USA and Brazil resolving their WTO cotton dispute was felt to provide a clear warning of what could happen within the wider WTO negotiations process (with the formal negotiations mirroring the ‘deal cutting’ arrangements used to conclude WTO disputes, generally leaving unresolved systemic issues of concern to the ACP. This was already held to be apparent in the December 2009 Geneva banana deal which resolved the long-running banana dispute in advance of a Doha deal but largely at the expense of traditional ACP banana suppliers.</p><p><b>3.2&nbsp; Putting WTO preference erosion in its wider context</b></p><p><b>&nbsp;</b>It can be argued that EU tariff concessions in a WTO context will further undermine the margins of tariff preferences which ACP suppliers currently enjoy, thereby undermining the competitive position of ACP exporters. While theoretically correct, in reality the value of ACP tariff preferences is first of all eroded firstly by the process of CAP reform. This is compounded by bilateral trade agreements which, by granting new tariff preferences to non-ACP producers, serve to erode the margins of tariff preferences enjoyed by ACP states.</p><p>Given the length of time required to finalise a WTO deal and set in place implementation modalities, the process is likely to compound the continuing processes of preference erosion rooted in the process of CAP reform and bilateral trade negotiations. Recent debates around the Mercosur–EU FTA negotiations are illustrative. Five years ago the prospect of a 500,000 tonne TRQ for beef imports negotiated at the multilateral level was the primary source of concern, whereas now the prospect of an imminent conclusion of bilateral negotiations between the EU and the Mercosur group is causing most concern. The impact of WTO tariff concessions cannot therefore be divorced from other tariff concessions that the EU is negotiating through bilateral trade agreements.</p><p>The potential losses to ACP exporters from a Doha agreement need to be seen in the wider context. Here a critical consideration is how the impacts of such an agreement interact with other EU policy choices in the affected sectors. These range from the future of sugar production quotas within the EU to the nature of bilateral tariff concessions under negotiations across a range of FTA agreement negotiations. A Doha agreement could be seen as exacerbate the current process of preference erosion while not itself being an underlying cause.</p><p><b>3.3 Dealing with sugar issues</b></p><p><b>&nbsp;</b>In many respects sugar is the key preference erosion issue for the ACP, given the effects of WTO provisions on EU sugar market prices. Such price effects cannot be separated from:</p><p>a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; the price effects of tariff concessions for sugar granted by the EU under bilateral FTA arrangements; and</p><p>b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; the price effects of the discontinuation of production quotas as a market management tool in the EU sugar sector.</p><p>For the ACP the critical concern is the cumulative effects on EU sugar market prices of changes in all of these areas. There is need therefore for a comprehensive consultation with the EC on the likely cumulative effects of sugar sector policy initiatives planned by the EC for the next three years. The consultation would need to include:</p>
<ul>

<li>internal reform of the EU sugar regime;</li>

<li>the treatment of sugar across a multiplicity of trade agreements currently being negotiated by the EU; and</li>

<li>the different options for dealing with sugar in the WTO tariff reduction negotiations.</li>

</ul>
<p>Only on the basis of these broader discussions can the best ACP option be determined for dealing with sugar issues in the WTO negotiations on tariffs.</p><p><b>3.4&nbsp; Re-energising the cotton discussions</b></p><p>The current debate on CAP reform and the next US Farm Bill is seen as an opportunity to re-energise the cotton discussions. One proposed line of approach would require the EU to end all coupled support for its cotton producers as part of the 2013 round of CAP reforms. It would furthermore require the EU to minimise the level of ‘box shifting’ taking place as part of the 2013 CAP reform process.</p><p>It is unclear, however, whether this is likely, given the March 2011 EU Council recognition of the need to maintain coupled payments in ‘sensitive’ sectors. It is unclear whether cotton would be considered such a sensitive sector. In view of the 58% decline that has taken place in EU cotton production since the initiation of reforms, southern European cotton growing countries may well consider the crop a ‘sensitive’ sector.</p><p>Any efforts to prioritise ACP cotton concerns within the current CAP reform discussions will need to pay close attention to the technical question of how the transition away from coupled support (which is an underlying principle of the CAP reform process) can best be managed. The financial crisis in Greece has highlighted the sensitivity of cotton sector issues in the EU (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Cotton/USDA-review-of-EU-cotton-sector-developments" target="_self">USDA review of EU cotton-sector developments</a>’, May 2011).</p><p><b>3.5&nbsp; Beyond the ACP–EU banana trade</b></p><p><b>&nbsp;</b>With the WTO banana dispute now largely resolved, the focus of ACP concern has shifted to the treatment of bananas under bilateral EU trade deals and the impact of such deals on the prices received for ACP banana exports on different components of the EU banana market.</p><p>The reduction in tariffs already under way is increasing competition within all parts of the EU banana market – conventional, organic and fair-trade banana exports. While data are scarce due to confidentiality concerns, analysis compiled by FAO suggests that in the organic market, as the market grows and the range of suppliers expands, price differentials previously enjoyed over convention banana export begin to close.</p><p>A similar trend may be under way in the fair-trade component of the market, where the highly competitive commercial practices of supermarket chains create tensions with fair-trade principles, particularly guarantees of sustainable prices for producers. This is likely to see a downward pressure on fair-trade prices as the number of fair-trade suppliers securing access to the EU market at reduced tariff rates expands. This is likely to undermine the price guarantees which underpin the fair-trade system.</p><p>This raises important questions related to:</p><p>a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; EU fair-trade labelling regulations (regarding the extension to supermarkets of the requirement to be bound by fair-trade standards, given their use of fair-trade products as market positioning tools);</p><p>b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; the functioning of ACP–EU banana supply chains (related to inequalities in power along the supply chain and the abuse of this power in commercial contract negotiations).</p><p>These issues are likely to take on growing significance, as the process of erosion of ACP banana sector tariff preferences (of which the WTO dimension is but one part) gains pace.</p><p>The key trading issues facing ACP banana exporters are now largely beyond the WTO framework. They are now concerned with EU labelling and regulatory requirements for quality-differentiated bananas, and the scope for joint ACP–EU policy initiatives to strengthen the functioning of the banana supply chain, given the vast inequalities in commercial power which characterise the various supply chains.</p><a name="eztoc495634_3_1" id="eztoc495634_3_1"></a><h3>Main sources</h3><p><b>The WTO negotiations process</b></p><p>1. ICTSD, ‘Ag negotiators prepare to kick-start Doha talks in January’, <i>Bridges Weekly Trade News Digest</i>, Volume 14, Number 43, 9 December 2010</p><p>
